Ubi. ‘Again when they had reached the level plain of another such like bridge, they were carried down again by an exactly similar fall of this lower bridge to one below it) ‘Ubi,’ ‘ ubi primum,’ ut primum,' and ‘quoties,' take the pluperfect subjunctive to express iteration in Livy, the plupersect indicative in Cicero. Compare l. 58, where we have the indicative. Thus Livy has ‘Id fetialis ubi dixisset, hastam in fines eorum mittebat‚’ i. 32. Cicero on the other hand says, ‘ Ubi pretio non aequitate-iura descripserat, Veneri iam et Libero reliquum tempus deberi arbitrabatur‚' Cic. Verr. v. 11. See Latin Grammar, ξ 211.
